3","1270":"1270","Abt 1240":"circa 1240","1258":"1258","1300":"1300","Abt 1265":"circa 1265","1210":"1210","1265":"1265","1317":"1317","Pathhead, Midlothian, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Pathhead, Midlothian, Schotland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Pathead, Midlothian, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Midlothian, Schotland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Crichton Castle, East Lothian, Scotland":"Crichton, Midlothian, Schotland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Pathhead, Midlothian, Scotland":"Pathhead, Midlothian, Schotland"},"en":{"Abt 1240–1283":"about 1240–1283","1240–1283":"1240–1283","1230–1300":"1230–1300","1265–1340":"1265–1340","1270–1317":"1270–1317","1210–Male":"1210–Deceased","about 1270":"about 1270","1340":"1340","1230":"1230","1240":"1240","1283":"1283","1270":"1270","Abt 1240":"about 1240","1258":"1258","1300":"1300","Abt 1265":"about 1265","1210":"1210","1265":"1265","1317":"1317","Pathhead, Midlothian, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Pathhead, Midlothian, Scotland, United Kingdom","Pathead, Midlothian, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Midlothian, Scotland, United Kingdom","Crichton Castle, East Lothian, Scotland":"Crichton, Midlothian, Scotland, United Kingdom","Pathhead, Midlothian, Scotland":"Pathhead, Midlothian, Scotland","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Crichton","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   Creighton   1."],"variants":[{"name":"Creighton","meanings":["Scottish and Irish: habitational name from Crichton, near Edinburgh, first recorded <i>c.</i> 1128 in the form <i>Crectune</i>, in 1287 as <i>Crecton</i>, and in 1360 as <i>Creychtona</i>. The name is probably an early hybrid compound of Old Welsh <i>creic</i> ‘rock’ + Older Scots <i>tun</i> ‘farm, settlement’ (Old English <i>tūn</i>). In Ireland and Britain, this form of the name is now found chiefly in northern Ireland; the more usual Scottish forms are   Crichton   and   Crighton  .","Irish: sometimes used for Gaelic <b>Ó Creacháin</b> or <b>Ó Criocháin</b> (see   Crehan  ).","English: habitational name from Creighton in Staffordshire, named with Celtic <i>creig</i> ‘rock’ + Old English <i>tūn</i> ‘settlement’."]}]},{"name":"Edna","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["In Ireland this has been used as an Anglicized form of Eithne . The name occurs in the apocryphal Book of Tobit, where it is the name of the mother of Sarah and stepmother of Tobias. This is said to be from Hebrew <i>῾ednah</i> ‘pleasure, delight’, and if so it is connected with the name of the Garden of   Eden .  The earliest known uses of the given name in England are in the 16th century, when it was probably imported from Ireland, although the spelling <i>Ednah</i> supports the idea that it was taken from the Bible."],"variants":[{"name":"Eithne","meanings":["Traditional name, apparently from <i>eithne</i> ‘kernel’, which was used as a term of praise in bardic poetry. St Eithne was a daughter of King Laoghaire and one of St Patrick's first converts."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Edna de Crichton was born about 1240, in Pathhead, Midlothian, Scotland, United Kingdom as the daughter of Pathhead. She married Thomas Crichton in 1258, in Pathhead, Midlothian, Scotland, United Kingdom. They wer